SAST security tool and DAST security tool what was that?

Great question, Nandeesh! Understanding SAST and DAST is very important in DevSecOps.

ğŸ” What is SAST and DAST?
| Type                    | SAST (Static Application Security Testing)                                   | DAST (Dynamic Application Security Testing)                      |
| ----------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------- |
| ğŸ” **What it does**     | Scans **source code** or binaries without running the app                    | Scans the **running application** like a black-box test          |
| ğŸ§  **When it's used**   | During **development/build phase** (early in CI pipeline)                    | During **runtime/testing phase** (after deployment or staging)   |
| ğŸ› ï¸ **How it works**    | Analyzes code for vulnerabilities like insecure functions, hardcoded secrets | Simulates real-world attacks on the app (SQLi, XSS, auth bypass) |
| ğŸ•µï¸ **Access required** | Needs **source code**                                                        | Doesnâ€™t need code, only the **web URL or endpoint**              |
| âš™ï¸ **Tools**            | Bandit, SonarQube, Semgrep, Snyk Code, Fortify SCA                           | OWASP ZAP, Burp Suite, Trivy (for web scan), Nikto, Snyk Web     |


âœ… Examples
ğŸ” SAST Example:
You're writing a Python script:
password = "mysecret"
â¡ï¸ Bandit or SonarQube will alert you: "Hardcoded credentials detected".

ğŸŒ DAST Example:
You deploy a website, and the login page doesnâ€™t block SQL injection.
â¡ï¸ OWASP ZAP will try sending:
' OR '1'='1
â¡ï¸ If it logs in â€” it flags it as a vulnerability.


ğŸ“Œ Summary:
| Type   | Use For                           | Example Tools                |
| ------ | --------------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| âœ… SAST | Secure coding & Dev phase         | Bandit, SonarQube, Snyk Code |
| âœ… DAST | Secure deployment & Runtime phase | OWASP ZAP, Burp, Trivy Web   |



Would you like help setting up both SAST + DAST tools in a GitHub Actions pipeline?
Yes, Nandeesh! Let's set up both SAST (Static) + DAST (Dynamic) tools in your GitHub Actions pipeline, step by step, using beginner-friendly tools:

âœ… Final Goal:
A GitHub Actions pipeline that:
Builds your Java WAR project with Maven
SAST: Scans source code with Bandit (for Python), SonarQube (for Java)
DAST: Scans your deployed web app with OWASP ZAP
Deploys to EC2/Tomcat (optional)
Rollback & backup (optional)

ğŸ”§ Step-by-Step Setup
âœ… 1. Set up your repo structure:
Your repo should look like:
/
â”œâ”€â”€ .github/workflows/devsecops.yml
â”œâ”€â”€ src/                  # Java source code
â”œâ”€â”€ pom.xml               # Maven build file
â”œâ”€â”€ app.py (optional)     # Python code (for Bandit)
â”œâ”€â”€ HTML/login.html       # Frontend
â””â”€â”€ README.md


âœ… 2. Add GitHub Actions pipeline (.github/workflows/devsecops.yml):
name: DevSecOps Full Scan

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]

jobs:
  devsecops:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
    - name: Checkout code
      uses: actions/checkout@v3

    - name: Set up JDK 17
      uses: actions/setup-java@v3
      with:
        java-version: '17'

    - name: Build with Maven
      run: mvn clean package

    # -------- SAST: Bandit for Python --------
    - name: Set up Python
      uses: actions/setup-python@v4
      with:
        python-version: '3.10'

    - name: Install Bandit
      run: pip install bandit

    - name: Run Bandit (Python SAST)
      run: bandit -r . -ll

    # -------- SAST: SonarQube for Java --------
    - name: SonarQube Scan (Java SAST)
      env:
        SONAR_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.SONAR_TOKEN }}
      run: |
        curl -sSLo sonar-scanner.zip https://binaries.sonarsource.com/Distribution/sonar-scanner-cli/sonar-scanner-cli-4.7.0.2747-linux.zip
        unzip sonar-scanner.zip
        ./sonar-scanner-*/bin/sonar-scanner \
          -Dsonar.projectKey=your-project-key \
          -Dsonar.sources=. \
          -Dsonar.host.url=https://sonarcloud.io \
          -Dsonar.login=$SONAR_TOKEN

    # -------- DAST: OWASP ZAP --------
    - name: Run OWASP ZAP baseline scan (DAST)
      uses: zaproxy/action-baseline@v0.10.0
      with:
        target: 'http://<your-ec2-ip>:8080'


ğŸ” 3. Set Secrets in GitHub:
Go to GitHub Repo â†’ Settings â†’ Secrets â†’ Actions and add:
SONAR_TOKEN â†’ from https://sonarcloud.io/account/security/
AWS_KEY_ID & AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY (for EC2 deploy, optional)

ğŸš€ 4. Optional Deployment & Rollback:
You can add later:
EC2 Deployment (scp + ssh)
S3 backup
Rollback logic with curl or rsync

ğŸ§ª Try It Out
Push code to main branch. GitHub Actions will:
Build WAR
Run Bandit (Python SAST)
Run SonarQube (Java SAST)
Run OWASP ZAP (DAST)


ğŸ” SAST vs. DAST:
| Type   | Tool Used        | Purpose                                                |
| ------ | ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| âœ… SAST | Trivy, SonarQube | Scan source code and dependencies                      |
| âœ… DAST | OWASP ZAP        | Test running app like a hacker does (Dynamic App Scan) |


âœ… Updated GitHub Actions Pipeline with SAST + DAST:
Below is your updated workflow that includes:

ğŸ” SAST: Trivy + SonarQube
ğŸš¨ DAST: OWASP ZAP (after app is deployed)

name: Full WAR CI/CD Pipeline

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]

env:
  EC2_IP: <your-ec2-ip>
  EC2_USER: ubuntu
  PRIVATE_KEY: ${{ secrets.EC2_PRIVATE_KEY }}
  WAR_NAME: NETFLIX.war
  REMOTE_PATH: /var/lib/tomcat9/webapps
  APP_URL: http://<your-ec2-ip>:8080/NETFLIX  # Update if needed

jobs:
  build-test-scan-deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
    - name: Checkout Code
      uses: actions/checkout@v3

    - name: Set up Java
      uses: actions/setup-java@v3
      with:
        java-version: '17'
        distribution: 'temurin'

    - name: Build WAR with Maven
      run: mvn clean package

    - name: Trivy Vulnerability Scan
      uses: aquasecurity/trivy-action@master
      with:
        scan-type: fs
        scan-ref: .

    - name: SonarQube Scan (SAST)
      uses: sonarsource/sonarcloud-github-action@master
      with:
        projectBaseDir: .
        args: >
          -Dsonar.projectKey=<your-key>
          -Dsonar.organization=<your-org>
          -Dsonar.host.url=https://sonarcloud.io
          -Dsonar.login=${{ secrets.SONAR_TOKEN }}

    - name: Deploy WAR to EC2 Tomcat
      run: |
        echo "$PRIVATE_KEY" > key.pem
        chmod 400 key.pem
        scp -i key.pem target/$WAR_NAME $EC2_USER@$EC2_IP:$REMOTE_PATH
        ssh -i key.pem $EC2_USER@$EC2_IP "sudo systemctl restart tomcat9"

    - name: (Optional) S3 Backup
      if: always()
      run: |
        echo "Uploading to S3 (optional)..."
        aws s3 cp target/$WAR_NAME s3://<your-bucket-name>/

    - name: Run OWASP ZAP Scan (DAST)
      uses: zaproxy/action-baseline@v0.7.0
      with:
        target: ${{ env.APP_URL }}


âœ… What this does:
| Step | Tool      | Type | Action                                                                |
| ---- | --------- | ---- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| âœ… 1  | Trivy     | SAST | Scans code & dependencies for vulnerabilities                         |
| âœ… 2  | SonarQube | SAST | Scans source code for bugs, smells, security issues                   |
| âœ… 3  | OWASP ZAP | DAST | Dynamically scans the **deployed** app for web attacks like XSS, SQLi |


ğŸ” Secrets You Must Add:
In GitHub repo â†’ Settings â†’ Secrets â†’ Actions:
EC2_PRIVATE_KEY
SONAR_TOKEN
(optional) AWS keys for S3: AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID, AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY

âœ… Done!
You now have a complete DevSecOps pipeline using:
ğŸ§ª Static Analysis (SAST) before deployment
ğŸ›¡ï¸ Dynamic Testing (DAST) after deployment






















